                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d666">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">715.1715/449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-06-20T11:00:00-05:45"
                            >June 20, 1931—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:08 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[114.] My June 12, 6 p.m. The Nicaraguan Senate approved yesterday the majority
                    report on the Nicaragua-Honduras boundary protocol. A copy of the report is not
                    yet available, but I understand it made radical changes in the protocol.
                    President Moncada has been in Masaya supporting the efforts of the
                    administration to obtain favorable action, and I am informed that the form in
                    which the protocol was approved represents the best compromise obtainable and
                    that otherwise the protocol would have been rejected. The impression here is
                    that Chamber of Deputies will approve the action of the Senate.</p>
                <p>I will report further as soon as I have reliable particulars.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Tegucigalpa.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanna</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
